	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/06/morning-agenda-a-haul-for-hedge-fund-moguls/" data-title="A Big Haul for Hedge Fund Moguls" data-description="Hedge fund managers are getting richer. | Bayer is buying Merck&#039;s consumer care business. | At Berkshire Hathaway, a culture of trust. | Barclays&#039; first-quarter earnings declined.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<h6 class="kicker"></h6>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Hedge fund managers, who heavily populate the so-called 1 percent in the United States, are getting richer. The 25 highest-earning hedge fund managers in the United States took home a total of $21.15 billion in compensation in 2013, according to an annual ranking published on Tuesday by Institutional Investorâs Alpha magazine, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/06/hedge-fund-moguls-pay-has-the-1-looking-up">DealBookâs Alexandra Stevenson writes</a></b>. The payday, earned in a year when most hedge fund managers fell short of market performance, is the highest since 2010 and 50 percent more than in 2012. <b>No women placed among the top 50</b>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Topping the list</b> was David A. Tepper, the founder of Appaloosa Management, who maintained his spot at No. 1, earning $3.5 billion last year. Steven A. Cohen of SAC Capital Advisors ranked No. 2 after bringing home $2.4 billion. John A. Paulson of Paulson &#038; Company earned $2.3 billion, ranking No. 3. Paychecks in 2013 were large, but <b>more remarkable were the multiples by which they increased</b> since Institutional Investor began collecting data on pay, Ms. Stevenson writes.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>For most hedge fund clients</b>, 2013 was disappointing, with the average fund returning 9.1 percent. By comparison, the Standard &#038; Poorâs 500-stock index soared 32.4 percent after accounting for dividends. Among the hedge funds that performed well in 2013 were the co-called Tiger Cubs, who benefited from soaring technology stocks, and activist investors. For its part, <b>2014 may not turn out to be as flush</b> for some hedge fund managers. Already, many of them have been dragged down by a market slump in the technology and biotechnology sectors.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">BAYER TO BUY MERCKâS CONSUMER CARE BUSINESS <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> The German drug maker Bayer said on Tuesday that it had agreed to acquire Merckâs consumer care business for $14.2 billion, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/06/bayer-to-buy-mercks-consumer-care-business-for-14-2-billion">Chad Bray writes in DealBook</a></b>. The deal will make Bayer one of the largest providers of over-the-counter products, giving it control of several well-known brand names, including Claritin, Coppertone and Dr. Schollâs.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Pro forma revenue of the company businesses in 2013 would have amounted to 5.5 billion euros, or about $7.6 billion. The deal is subject to regulatory approval and is <b>expected to close in the second half of 2014</b>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">IN BERKSHIRE WE TRUST <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> During Berkshire Hathawayâs annual meeting last weekend, Charlie Munger, Berkshireâs vice chairman and Warren E. Buffettâs best friend, offered a counternarrative to the distrustful culture of most businesses, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/05/berkshires-radical-strategy-trust">Andrew Ross Sorkin writes in the DealBook column</a></b>. Instead of filling your ranks with lawyers and compliance people, Mr. Munger argued, <b>hire people that you actually trust</b> and let them do their job.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Mr. Munger was not just talk</b>: Berkshire Hathaway is the fifth-largest company in the United States, with about $162.5 billion in revenue and 300,000 employees worldwide, but it has no general counsel that oversees the holding companyâs units and no human resources department. âIf that sounds like a corporate utopia, thatâs probably because it is,â Mr. Sorkin writes.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>There may, however, be some truth to Mr. Mungerâs view</b>. âBehavioral scientists and psychologists have long contended that âtrustâ is, to some degree, one of the most powerful forces within organizations,â Mr. Sorkin adds. Indeed, despite the increase in lawyers and compliance officers, bad behavior continues. Still, a trust-based system &#8220;<b>puts a lot of emphasis on selecting the right people</b>,â Mr. Sorkin writes, and not all industries, including the financial industry, may be equal when it comes to trust. âYouâre never going to have perfect behavior in a miasma of easy money,â Mr. Munger said over the weekend.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> The report on the <b>international trade deficit</b> is out at 8:30 a.m. <b>Jeremy C. Stein</b>, a Federal Reserve governor, gives a speech in New York at 6:15 p.m. <b>The Walt Disney Company</b> reports earnings after the market closes. <b>Robert H. Benmosche</b>, the chief executive of the American International Group, is on Fox Business Network at 9:40 a.m. The hedge fund magnate <b>David Einhorn</b> is on Bloomberg TV at 11 a.m.</p>
